{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603353"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:36:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:36:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15743"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15743"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.13,0.38,0.13,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8434"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62427"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8434"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15743"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47874"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8579"},{"type":"tags","id":"10580"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"},{"type":"tags","id":"10631"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20303"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62427"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes fecundability?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The capacity to produce viable gametes","The likelihood of having a live birth","The probability of conception per menstrual cycle","The cumulative probability of pregnancy over 12 months","The ability to carry a pregnancy to term"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding fecundability is crucial for counselling patients about fertility expectations. \u003Cstrong\u003EThe probability of conception per menstrual cycle\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct definition of fecundability. This probability is approximately 20-25% in young, healthy couples with regular unprotected intercourse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe ability to carry a pregnancy to term\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the concept of maintaining a viable pregnancy through gestation, which is different from the probability of achieving conception in a given cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe cumulative probability of pregnancy over 12 months\u003C/strong\u003E is fertility, which is approximately 85% in young couples. This is distinct from fecundability as it represents the chance of pregnancy over multiple cycles rather than per individual cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe likelihood of having a live birth\u003C/strong\u003E encompasses multiple factors beyond conception, including the probability of maintaining pregnancy and successful delivery. This is not fecundability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe capacity to produce viable gametes\u003C/strong\u003E refers to gametogenesis, which is a prerequisite for fertility but does not describe the probability of conception per cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFecundability is influenced by multiple factors including maternal age, timing of intercourse relative to ovulation, and underlying fertility factors. It peaks in the early 20s and gradually declines with age, particularly after age 35.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fecundability is the probability of achieving pregnancy within one menstrual cycle of regular unprotected intercourse.","Peak fecundability occurs in the early 20s and declines with advancing maternal age.","Normal fecundability in young couples is approximately 20-25% per cycle."],"references":["Vander Borght M, Wyns C. Fertility and infertility: Definition and epidemiology. Clin Biochem. 2018 Dec;62:2-10. doi: 10.1016/j.clinbiochem.2018.03.012. Epub 2018 Mar 16. PMID: 29555319","Smarr MM, Sapra KJ, Gemmill A, Kahn LG, Wise LA, Lynch CD, Factor-Litvak P, Mumford SL, Skakkebaek NE, Slama R, Lobdell DT, Stanford JB, Jensen TK, Boyle EH, Eisenberg ML, Turek PJ, Sundaram R, Thoma ME, Buck Louis GM. Is human fecundity changing? A discussion of research and data gaps precluding us from having an answer. Hum Reprod. 2017 Mar 1;32(3):499-504. doi: 10.1093/humrep/dew361. PMID: 28137753; PMCID: PMC5850610","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47874"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15743"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47874"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T18:37:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T18:00:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8434"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62427"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synon